                  {
                    "kind": "text",
                    "data": "Now I have the full picture. Here's what the `.bd` file adds:\n\n---\n\n## What the BD file reveals\n\n### AXI Address Map\n\nEach peripheral gets a 64K window in the PS's AXI address space (base `0x8000_0000`):\n\n| Address | Peripheral | Purpose |\n|---|---|---|\n| `0x8000_0000` | axi_gpio_motor0 | Write control vector → motor 0; Read position ← motor 0 |\n| `0x8001_0000` | axi_gpio_motor1 | motor 1 |\n| `0x8002_0000` | axi_gpio_motor2 | motor 2 |\n| `0x8003_0000` | axi_gpio_motor3 | motor 3 |\n| `0x8004_0000` | axi_gpio_motor4 | motor 4 |\n| `0x8005_0000` | axi_gpio_motor5 | motor 5 |\n| `0x8006_0000` | axi_gpio_motor6 | motor 6 |\n| `0x8007_0000` | axi_gpio_motor7 | motor 7 |\n| `0x8008_0000` | axi_gpio_motor8 | motor 8 |\n| `0x8009_0000` | axi_gpio_motor9 | motor 9 |\n| `0x800A_0000` | axi_gpio_10 | motor 10 |\n| `0x800B_0000` | axi_gpio_motor11 | motor 11 |\n| `0x800C_0000` | axi_gpio_motor12 | motor 12 |\n| `0x800D_0000` | axi_gpio_motor13 | motor 13 |\n| `0x800E_0000` | axi_iic_0 | I2C (BMI270 IMU) |\n| `0x800F_0000` | axi_intc_0 | Interrupt controller |\n| `0x8010_0000` | axi_gpio_watchdog | Watchdog toggle signal |\n\n### How each AXI GPIO is wired\n\nEach `axi_gpio_motorN` is a dual-channel GPIO:\n- **Channel 1 output** (`gpio_io_o`) → `motor_controller_N/control_vector_in` — PS writes the 15-bit control vector here\n- **Channel 2 input** (`gpio2_io_i`) ← `motor_controller_N/motor_pos` — PS reads the 16-bit encoder position back here\n\nSo the PS uses a single peripheral (one AXI GPIO) per motor for both command and feedback.\n\n### Clocks\n\n- `pl_clk0` (from PS, raw) → feeds all 14 motor controllers and the watchdog directly\n- `pl_clk0` also → `clk_wiz_0` which generates a **200 MHz** clock (`clk_out2`) → feeds the entire AXI fabric (interconnect, all GPIO blocks, IIC, INTC)\n\nSo motor controllers run at the PS's raw PL clock frequency, while AXI runs at 200 MHz.\n\n### Watchdog wiring\n\n- PS writes a toggling bit to `axi_gpio_watchdog` → `watchdog_0/wdt_sig`\n- `watchdog_0/watchdog_out` → `en` pin of **all 14 motor controllers** simultaneously\n- `watchdog_out` also drives **user_led1** — so the LED is on when the watchdog is healthy and goes dark when it trips\n\n### One gap: motor_controller_8's `en`\n\nMotor 8 is included in the watchdog net — all 14 are covered. No motor is excluded from the safety shutdown.\n\n---\n\nThe system is now fully understood. The software flow is: write a 15-bit control word to `0x8000_N000` (where N is the motor index × 0x10000) to command a motor, read back 16 bits from the same peripheral's channel 2 for position, and periodically toggle a bit at `0x8010_0000` to keep the watchdog alive."
