            "kind": "text",
            "data": "Now I have a thorough picture of the whole system. Here's the description:\n\n---\n\n## SIMBA Rover FPGA System (Vivado)\n\nThis is the FPGA fabric design for a **6-wheeled rover with independent steering on each wheel**, targeting the **AMD/Xilinx Kria SOM** (Zynq UltraScale+ based). The design lives in `vivado/` and consists of custom RTL modules and a block diagram.\n\n---\n\n### Hardware Platform\n\n- **Target**: Kria KV260/KR260 SOM (Zynq UltraScale+ PS+PL)\n- **I/O**: 4x PMOD connectors + Raspberry Pi GPIO header, all at LVCMOS33\n- **I2C**: RPi header pins (AE15/AE14) — used for the BMI270 IMU (see `rover/` code)\n\n---\n\n### Motor Topology\n\nThe rover has **14 motors total** (motors 0–13), organized as 7 wheel positions × 2 motors each:\n\n| Position | Steer Motor | Wheel Motor |\n|---|---|---|\n| Rear Right | motor 0 | motor 1 |\n| Front Right | motor 2 | motor 3 |\n| Front Left | motor 4 | motor 5 |\n| Rear Left | motor 6 | motor 7 |\n| Middle Left | — | motor 8 |\n| Middle Right | — | motor 9 |\n| unused/extra | motors 10–13 | — |\n\nEach motor gets a 2-wire H-bridge output and a 2-wire quadrature encoder input, all routed through the PMOD/RPi GPIO pins.\n\n---\n\n### RTL Module Hierarchy\n\n```\nmotor_controller (top custom IP)\n├── control_signal_decoder   — unpacks 15-bit AXI control vector into fields\n├── H_Bridge_Driver          — drives the H-bridge\n│   └── PWM_Generator        — variable-frequency PWM (8-bit duty, 3-bit clock divisor)\n└── quadDecoder              — quadrature encoder position counter (16-bit)\n    └── cntr_udclr_nb        — generic n-bit up/down counter with async reset\n```\n\n**Control vector format** (15 bits, defined in `motor_controller_signals.vh`):\n\n| Bits | Field | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| [7:0] | motor_duty_in | PWM duty cycle (0–255) |\n| [10:8] | clk_divisor | Selects PWM frequency (divides clock by 2^N) |\n| [11] | motor_dir | Direction |\n| [12] | h_bridge_en | Enable H-bridge |\n| [13] | dec_clr | Clear encoder counter |\n| [14] | dec_en | Enable encoder counting |\n\nThe motor outputs a 16-bit position readback from the quadrature decoder.\n\n**Watchdog** (`watchdog.v`): Monitors a toggling signal from the PS. If the signal stops toggling for >5ms (500,000 cycles at 100MHz), it pulls the `en` line low, which disables all H-bridges. This is a safety kill-switch — if the software crashes or hangs, the motors stop.\n\n---\n\n### Block Diagram (Kria_BD)\n\nThe block diagram instantiates:\n- **Zynq UltraScale+ PS** (`zynq_ultra_ps_e_0`) — the ARM processor running the rover software\n- **14× motor_controller** custom IP instances (one per motor)\n- **15× AXI GPIO** blocks — used to read encoder positions back to the PS\n- **1× AXI IIC** — I2C master for the BMI270 IMU\n- **1× AXI INTC** — interrupt controller\n- **AXI interconnect/crossbar** (`xbar_0`, `tier2_xbar_0/1/2`, `ps8_0_axi_periph`) — routes AXI-Lite from PS to all peripherals\n- **Clock wizard** (`clk_wiz_0`) + **proc_sys_reset** — generates and manages the 100MHz PL clock\n- **xlconstant** — ties off unused signals\n- **watchdog** instance — safety timer\n\nThe PS writes control vectors over AXI-Lite to each motor controller, and reads back encoder positions via AXI GPIO. The watchdog must be periodically toggled by software or all motors shut off.\n\n---\n\n### Summary\n\nThe FPGA acts as a **motor control coprocessor** for the Kria's ARM cores. The PS (running the C/C++ rover code in `rover/`) sends PWM duty, direction, and enable commands to 14 independent motor controllers over AXI, reads back 16-bit quadrature encoder positions, communicates with the IMU over I2C, and must keep the watchdog alive to keep the motors running."
          }
